<subSubSection id="05FBA266B5FDABB25D360319CA069615" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="notes">
<paragraph id="36D6D62F3791F3818E8083D766AA0CE7" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D820EFB16136A23A8E525970738EA698" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="5" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
In Table 
<tableCitation id="7515571F748FC8CCEEC3AB68FEEFD3E2" captionStartId="T3" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/C9322C97B8908160F74CBCD55C5DACA4" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" tableUuid="C9322C97B8908160F74CBCD55C5DACA4">3</tableCitation>
, the most important character states of the shells and the genital organs of the 
<taxonomicName id="549ED80BE418A3C16EF987F4AD5EC2D5" lsidName="" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="tribe" tribe="Otalini">Otalini</taxonomicName>
subgroup according to 
<bibRefCitation id="8C752F23286AC6379963818E519D52BE" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2014.11.014" author="Razkin, O" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="99 - 117" refId="B31" refString="Razkin, O, Gomez-Moliner, BJ, Prieto, CE, Martinez-Orti, A, Arrebola, R, Munoz, B, Chueca, LJ, Madeira, MJ, 2015. Molecular phylogeny of the western Palaearctic Helicoidea (Gastropoda, Stylommatophora). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 83: 99 - 117" title="Molecular phylogeny of the western Palaearctic Helicoidea (Gastropoda, Stylommatophora)." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2014.11.014" volume="83" year="2015">Razkin et al. (2015</bibRefCitation>
: 108, 
<figureCitation id="36D743DEB92E3F73F7A07A0E43F5E62A" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Cantareus apertus. Syntype of Helix aperta NHMW-MO 14005, shell diameter 28.75 mm. Shell in A frontal B dorsal C lateral and D apical views E labels of the syntype lot. Photographs NHMW, x 1.5." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.876.36472.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/340653" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.876.36472.figure2">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) including the genera 
<taxonomicName id="FF0732F5EE7BF2326D059A4C03F4FBA8" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Cantareus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cantareus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="075D5F968DC683E76BF0BDD518298F1C" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Cantareus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="7F81AC124692CF7B64F3489977056B2B" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Cornu" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cornu" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B79599226E615FC93F888CB4176B28A1" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Cornu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="9427FE2AF68BABA3DDB89DD6FE7A7890" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Rossmaessleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rossmaessleria" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AA21F5FA625782376090179D7A15898B" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Rossmaessleria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are shown. Within the 
<taxonomicName id="C5BB58D666D8BD5627283572D5ABD7F8" lsidName="" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="tribe" tribe="Otalini">Otalini</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="BDC292B0041DA2D36001D6F3D8F30221" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Cantareus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cantareus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DCA20E4782087001A6AB60B544B1E809" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Cantareus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A1F36DFEA0D2588D1DB16F02A7D723B5" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Cornu" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cornu" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A73C0168FB4E83ABE0C29F70F3B38F3B" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Cornu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="6DCA330F9D13B47EE1EE340191DE4992" authority="Monterosato, 1894" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1894" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Erctella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Erctella" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0C52CDA83BDE0A41FF511A455B643605" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Erctella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share the synapomorphy of a globular to slightly conical shell, other genera in the tribe tend to have more flattened shells (character 1). In all other shell traits, there is no apomorphy that discriminates between 
<taxonomicName id="63384BDCE4F08EA346413F02420EF7FC" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Cantareus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cantareus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C802CA5DD673C8834BC39401DAC52347" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Cantareus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5863DC99560E1D148D1E19DE60BE5A2" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Cornu" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cornu" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6F24D5A1844F686252D71F8A3F729BF3" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Cornu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="EA801825B21116AD976BB79C21B00409" authority="Monterosato, 1894" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1894" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Erctella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Erctella" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DB72E33C45C94657C71F1AE89EEB1909" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Erctella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on generic level. On the level of the genital organs, the three genera share the synapomophy of the simple pore connecting epiphallus and penial chamber (char 
<pageBreakToken id="164BE409A6297C387B2AC21D41FE3094" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" start="start">acter</pageBreakToken>
8), while 
<taxonomicName id="00DF5895F191CEEE8D6BAE2C1A059F5D" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Rossmaessleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rossmaessleria" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3149B667C58EAE449FDCFDE2F3852C37" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Rossmaessleria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows the plesiomophic state with two functional penial papillae. In 
<taxonomicName id="9790D438748D217BC11797374AEA5CF8" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Cornu" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cornu" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3F79CD72989073EBD23C942FF5C69CAA" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cornu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the flagellum is much longer than in the other genera. The phylogenetic value of this character state is not clear within the 
<taxonomicName id="2E5EAB6AF89168735ED6C3ADA6EFE3F9" lsidName="" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" rank="tribe" tribe="Otalini">Otalini</taxonomicName>
, within the 
<taxonomicName id="AC5984FC3C6FEE2C4843FF031DECF510" lsidName="" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" rank="tribe" tribe="Helicini">Helicini</taxonomicName>
, it is considered a plesiomorphy (
<bibRefCitation id="01248244B95615E58E7FA71AA9C60B58" author="Neubert, E" journalOrPublisher="Contribution to Natural History" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="1 - 200" refId="B24" refString="Neubert, E, 2014. Revision of Helix (Linnaeus, 1758) in its eastern Mediterranean distribution area, and reassignment of Helixgodetiana (Kobelt, 1878) to Maltzanella (Hesse, 1917) (Gastropoda, Pulmonata, Helicidae). Contribution to Natural History 26: 1 - 200" title="Revision of Helix (Linnaeus, 1758) in its eastern Mediterranean distribution area, and reassignment of Helixgodetiana (Kobelt, 1878) to Maltzanella (Hesse, 1917) (Gastropoda, Pulmonata, Helicidae)." volume="26" year="2014">Neubert 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Other character states like ratios in the bursa copulatrix complex (character 10). A massive atrial stimulator can be found in 
<taxonomicName id="C8B5721054AE5CAC22EBBFFCAD6AE56D" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Cantareus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cantareus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1953DCC4C63A153FB678853FF9EED2F9" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cantareus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="89ABEC820C5913C5AC947C9058E609A4" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Cornu" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cornu" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="38DB051AFBB6178BA627787FEEAE64FB" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cornu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, while in 
<taxonomicName id="853F82BE822752BD8B708E33AD81F79B" authority="Monterosato, 1894" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1894" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Erctella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Erctella" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DC3CE0B7F5E51AEB02CC8A2527324C7" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Erctella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is relatively small (character 11). Large and massive stimulators are found in many taxa of 
<taxonomicName id="ED9AC1DFD6E778D8692CDE19C6DD3D02" family="Helicidae" lsidName="" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" rank="family">Helicidae</taxonomicName>
, so a reduction of this system is here interpreted as an apomorphic character state.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2295C4FF54DF8B28BCA75CEDD39B439B" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis id="C0979851F026F988C55D58D7541253B8" bold="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Remarks.</emphasis>
The change of the status of 
<taxonomicName id="342E4DE96486AC924AF21C9E4D03087A" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Cantareus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cantareus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="97FF090BA6C4220BA99C5E414E2F6334" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cantareus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from a monotypic to a polytypic genus causes some nomenclatorial problems. The type species of the genus is 
<taxonomicName id="48628C0F2E9D3559192AFA8491CF8122" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Helix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Helix naticoides" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="naticoides">
<emphasis id="EF561BE1A540DAF50FEBCE439A28B3B1" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Helix naticoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Draparnaud, 1801 from France, which so far has been considered a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="77A929EB7054D9C234FCC1DA5D79C962" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Helix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Helix aperta" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="aperta">
<emphasis id="CCCB3D7215B7E1D40A7D5D7B422D65BB" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Helix aperta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Born, 1778, with the specimen preserved in the Born collection in the NHMW as the name bearing syntype of 
<taxonomicName id="89D8C69D8F21A432E02FAC8554317A43" genus="Columbrina" lsidName="Columbrina aperta" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" rank="species" species="aperta">
<emphasis id="9A1058790DEDE97BCCDAB03A48C4CCB8" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">aperta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="D488C46CF4148D97EA14F9B532862CDC" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Cantareus apertus. Syntype of Helix aperta NHMW-MO 14005, shell diameter 28.75 mm. Shell in A frontal B dorsal C lateral and D apical views E labels of the syntype lot. Photographs NHMW, x 1.5." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.876.36472.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/340653" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.876.36472.figure2">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).The origin of 
<normalizedToken id="127C4B31692196DC4BF8664E74D2EAE5" originalValue="Born’s">Born's</normalizedToken>
specimen is unknown, and there are almost no shell morphological differences to the Algerian lineage, which proved to represent a separate species (
<figureCitation id="52C69A21A8C9FA0D9D2372F7D01669B3" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Combined RaxML and Bayesian tree of Cantareus, Cornu, and Erctella, using COI, 16 S, H 3, 28 S, and ITS 2." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.876.36472.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/340677" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.876.36472.figure1">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). The correct origin of 
<normalizedToken id="E1A8853AA8A59A6FD2C7A312CD19CB67" originalValue="Born’s">Born's</normalizedToken>
specimen could probably be clarified genetically by applying NGS methods using shell fragments of the syntype specimen, but this is beyond the scope of this paper.
</paragraph>
